docs.lead_paragraph: Witold Gombrowicz (1904-1969), the Polish novelist and playwright, was that melancholy phenomenon in literature, the minor writer on to a major vision. Gombrowicz conceived of an "interhuman sphere," which he also called "Form," that represented the collective shape he saw mankind assuming. "Being united," he wrote, "people impose on one another such or such a mode of being, talking, acting. . . . Every person deforms other persons while being simultaneously deformed by them."

docs.lead_paragraph: IF the period of the musical theater that began with Rodgers and Hammerstein and "Okla homal" and hit its peak with Lerner and Loewe and "My Fair Lady" has actually run its course--and whatever blood remains in it has been getting thinner and thinner-- Coco provides it with a reasonably graceful and appropriate terminal point.
